Red Wine Quality Exploration

Eric

October 24, 2017

Red Wine Quality Exploration by Eric

“Tasty like a fine wine” - ever hear this expression before? Ever wonder what makes wine, a fermented grape juice by nature, taste better with age? Does all wine taste better with age? While the age of wine is interesting in measuring the quality of it, this data exploration project will dive into the chemical properties of red wine and explore what makes a good red wine better than others.

Univariate Plots Section

About the Data

This report explores over 1500 observations containing information about 12 different attributes of the wine.

Wine Quality Distribution

The minimum value of the quality of wine is a 3 and the highest scored observation received an 8 for wine quality. The median quality score equals 6 and the bulk of the quality scores fall within the [5,6] range.

One thing that stood out in these plots of the wine quality is that the majority of the observations fall into the average wine quality bucket. This suggests the data set might not be the most trusted data as the majority of wine tasted could have been in the medium price range or did the data get collected at a specific location (ie a gas station or convenience store)? A more concrete concern with this data is how the poor and excellent wine qualities have low observation counts. These factors will have to go through some sort of normalization in order to smooth out the distributions.

Distributions For the Remaining Attributes

Univariate Analysis

The univariate plots shed light to the behavior of the various chemical properties of the wine data.

Structure of the Dataset

  • The following properties are normally distributed: Volatile acidity, Density, pH
  • The following properties are positively skewed: Fixed acidity, Citric acid, Free sulfur dioxide, Total sulfur dioxide, Sulphates, Alcohol
  • The following properties are long-tailed skewed: Residual sugar, Chlorides

Main Feature of Interest

Main feature of interest in the data is quality of the wine. Much of the bivariate analysis should be centered around this feature as the independent variable. This exploration will hopefully lead to an understanding of which factors contribute / how they contribute to the quality of wine.

Unusual Distributions Investigated

For the features following a skewed or long-tailed distribution, I performed arithmetic operations on the data in order to transform them closer to a normal distribution.

The correlation matrix gives a preview into what the bivariate scatterplots look like between quality and the other features.

Top Correlated Features (To Quality)

I ran Pearson’s correlation tests between the wine quality against the remaining wine properties and found 4 features with a correlation coefficient of at least 0.2 with the wine quality:

  • Alcohol, r = 0.476
  • Volatile.acidity, r = -0.391
  • Sulphates, r = 0.251
  • Citric.acid, r = 0.226

Interesting Relationships Between the Other Features (not the main feature(s)

of interest)?

Found strong correlation between:

  • Citric.acid vs fixed.acidity , r = 0.672
  • Density vs fixed.acidity , r = 0.668
  • pH vs fixed.acidity , r = 0.683
  • Total.sulfur.dioxide vs free.sulfur.dioxide , r = 0.668

Bivariate Box Plots - A Bivariate Quality Investigation

Building off of the correlation calculated, box plots were created below to observe anythingelse that may have not been captured between the bivariate correlation table.

Beginning with the supporting features to the quality feature, that is, the main feature of interest, I’m going to explore acidity (fixed, volatile, citric) and pH since they could have a big impact on the quality of the wine. It’s important to understand too acidic of wine can give off a strong vinegar taste. Also, wine with a pH outside the range of 3-4 could be too basic or too acidic and affect the taste.

The plots for the attributes of acidity and pH are below,

  • Fixed.acidity - As fixed acidity increases or decreases, there’s little effect to the quality. The mean values of fixed acidity don’t fluctuate much as quality increases.
  • Volatile.acidity - As volatile acidity increases, the quality of wine decreases, so there’s an inverse relationship between the two.
  • Citric.acid - As citric acid increases, there’s a slight uptick in wine quality.
  • pH - As pH decreases (also, becomes more acidic), the quality of wine slightly increases as well.

I wanted to explore how the different types of acid affected the pH. Plots comparing to the3 types of acid are below.

Putting these 3 plots on the same grid made it easier to see how for volatile acid the negative correlation that exists between pH and acid doesn’t hold true here.

Plotted below are the remaining attributes compared to wine quality.

  • Residual.sugar - Residual sugar content in wine doesn’t seem to have any affect on the quality as the mean levels stay relatively equal for varying quality of wine.
  • Chlorides - As chlorides decrease, there’s a very minor increase in the quality.
  • Free.sulfur.dioxide - For free sulfur dioxide, it would appear that absolutely low levels on dioxide results in absolutely low levels of quality wine. While, absolutely high levels of dioxide results in average quality (~ 4.5 - 6.5).
  • Total.sulfur.dioxide - This attribute takes on a similar patter as free sulfur dioxide.
  • Density - As density decreases, the quality of wine has a slight increase.
  • Sulphates - As sulphates increase, the quality of wine increases as well.

Since quality and alcohol held the strongest correlation coefficient of over 0.4 I decided to perform a deeper investigation of the attribute by also taking a look at how the quality_rank attribute performed with varying levels of alcohol.

Bivariate Plots - Quality vs Alcohol

The box plot of quality vs alcohol demonstrates the strong correlation coefficient between the two attributes.

A puzzling aspect is how there still exists a handful of outliers in the box plot. This suggests alcohol isn’t the only attribute with a contribution to the quality of wine. The bivariate correlation of quality supports this idea. A linear model was calculated below to gain insight into just how much other attributes and alcohol affect the quality of wine.

Multivariate Plots Section

Effect of Acids on Wine Quality

Based on the bivariate investigation of the role acids play in the quality of wine we know that the more acidic a wine is, the higher the quality is. Let’s investigate how different combinations of acids can affect the quality.

  • Fixed Acidity by Citric Acid and Quality Rank - There doesn’t seem to be any correlation to the wine quality with these two variables.
  • Fixed Acidity by Volatile Acidity and Quality Rank - There doesn’t seem to be any correlation to the wine quality with these two variables.
  • Volatile Acidity by Citric Acid and Quality Rank - Lower amounts of volatile acidity and higher amounts of citric acid lead to better quality wine.
  • Fixed Acidity by Citric Acid - There doesn’t seem to be any correlation to the wine quality with these two variables.

Effect of Alcohol and Other Attributes on Wine Quality

Furthering the investigation into which attributes affect the quality of wine, I held alcohol as an independent variable to test whether different variables affected the quality of wine.

In this relationship, wine quality increases as fixed acidity content increases and alcohol concentration decreases.

As the amount of volatile acidity decreases and the amount of alcohol increases, the quality of wine seems to increase as well.

With higher citric acid and lower alcohol concentration, the wine quality increases.

There doesn’t seem to be any correlation with here between residual sugar and quality.

Chlorides behaves in a similar way as residual sugar does with quality.

As free sulfur dioxide concentration decreases and alcohol increases, the quality of wine decreases.

As pH decreases and alcohol concentration increases, wine quality improves.

As sulphate concentration increases and alcohol concentration increases, the quality of wine increases as well. Interesting to note how excellent wine seems to hover around .75 sulphates level even at varying values of alcohol.

Multivariate Analysis

Linear Modeling

Using the linear model function I was able to build a model to predict the outcome variable, quality, using a handful of explanatory (or predictor) variables in the wine dataset.

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = as.numeric(quality) ~ fixed.acidity + volatile.acidity + 
##     chlorides + total.sulfur.dioxide + sulphates + alcohol, data = wine_samp)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.25056 -0.37308 -0.05816  0.43944  1.94517 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                        Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)           2.5724016  0.4261914   6.036 3.11e-09 ***
## fixed.acidity         0.0434652  0.0185290   2.346   0.0194 *  
## volatile.acidity     -1.1319573  0.1740927  -6.502 1.95e-10 ***
## chlorides            -1.4114831  0.6636815  -2.127   0.0339 *  
## total.sulfur.dioxide -0.0009416  0.0009826  -0.958   0.3384    
## sulphates             0.8145057  0.1933689   4.212 3.01e-05 ***
## alcohol               0.2821132  0.0305322   9.240  < 2e-16 ***

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

## Multiple R-squared:   0.36,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.3522 
## F-statistic: 46.21 on 6 and 493 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The final linear model for wine quality becomes:

lm(quality) = 3.080 + 0.040fixed.acidity - 1.039volatile.acidity - 2.164chlorides - 0.002total.sulfur.dioxide + 0.753sulphates + 0.244alcohol

Analysis of Linear Model

I first ran the linear model using the top 8 correlated variables to quality to determine the significance of the variables and limit the model to only include signifcantly important predictor variables. Using the signifiance legend codes as a guide I kept any variable with at least a “*" next to it for the final model feature set. The reason I used the signifance codes as a way to interpret linear model effectiveness is because the of the low R squared value I kept calculating in the various linear models. It would seem that the vast majority of wine observations belonging to the average quality rank could come into play here as a more complete data set - one with a more level-loaded wine quality - could have aided in developing a stronger model.

Reflection

This red wine dataset contains 1599 observations with 11 variables on various chemical properties. With the main feature of interest being the quality of wine, this investigation’s objective was to explore the relationship between the rest of the features and the wine quality.

Initial bivariate exploration revealed that only a handful of features hold a reasonable correlation to the wine quality. For the purposes of this investigation, the top 4 most highest correlation coefficients to quality - alcohol, volatile acidity, sulphates, and citric acid - were used in much of the data visualizations.

It was surprising to me how some of the other features aren’t strongly correlated with the wine quality. I would assume pH, for example, would play a big role into determining the quality of wine.

Another surprise / struggle appeared when I realized the uneven distribution of observations across the 3 levels of wine quality ranking - poor, average, excellent. We saw how in the linear model for predicting wine quality, the traditional approach for using R squared values as a gauge for model effectiveness did not work with this particular dataset (since all the values of models were well below acceptance ranges). A data collection effort to include more wines from poor and excellent rankings would go a long way in improving the capability of models for predicting the quality of wine.

In terms of the future work to be done for improving the dataset, including different components of red wine into the data could help lead to more powerful linear models as well. For example, I’m curious to see how age would affect the quality of wines. Is older-aged wine really worth the bump in retail tag? Or does the price of wine help determine the quality? These questions could help spark an effort to form a dataset with the potential to gain insight and strong conclusions from.
